{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":37554,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-01T19:48:11.237Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eHi all,\u003cbr\u003e\nI’m trying to use emission texture to make parts of a texture fully lit at all times. I noticed in shader code that since sample from emission map is multiplied by emission color, I should probably set emission color to white:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"onebox githubblob\"\u003e\n  \u003cheader class=\"source\"\u003e\n      \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/xamarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Shaders/HLSL/LitSolid.hlsl#L312\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003egithub.com\u003c/a\u003e\n  \u003c/header\u003e\n  \u003carticle class=\"onebox-body\"\u003e\n    \u003ch4\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://github.com/xamarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Shaders/HLSL/LitSolid.hlsl#L312\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003examarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Shaders/HLSL/LitSolid.hlsl#L312\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cpre class=\"onebox\"\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-hlsl\"\u003e\u003col class=\"start lines\" start=\"302\" style=\"counter-reset: li-counter 301 ;\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e            finalColor += lightInput.rgb * diffColor.rgb + lightSpecColor * specColor;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #endif\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #ifdef ENVCUBEMAP\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e            finalColor += cMatEnvMapColor * SampleCube(EnvCubeMap, reflect(iReflectionVec, normal)).rgb;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #endif\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #ifdef LIGHTMAP\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e            finalColor += Sample2D(EmissiveMap, iTexCoord2).rgb * diffColor.rgb;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #endif\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #ifdef EMISSIVEMAP\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli class=\"selected\"\u003e            finalColor += cMatEmissiveColor * Sample2D(EmissiveMap, iTexCoord.xy).rgb;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #else\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e            finalColor += cMatEmissiveColor;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        #endif\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e        oColor = float4(GetFog(finalColor, fogFactor), diffColor.a);\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e    #endif\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e}\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\n\n  \u003c/article\u003e\n  \u003cdiv class=\"onebox-metadata\"\u003e\n    \n    \n  \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003cdiv style=\"clear: both\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSo I did, and it looks great when in full darkness. But when scene is lit, suddenly these areas turn too bright. So I looked at the technuique:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"onebox githubblob\"\u003e\n  \u003cheader class=\"source\"\u003e\n      \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/xamarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Techniques/DiffEmissiveAlpha.xml#L2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003egithub.com\u003c/a\u003e\n  \u003c/header\u003e\n  \u003carticle class=\"onebox-body\"\u003e\n    \u003ch4\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://github.com/xamarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Techniques/DiffEmissiveAlpha.xml#L2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003examarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Techniques/DiffEmissiveAlpha.xml#L2\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cpre class=\"onebox\"\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-xml\"\u003e\u003col class=\"start lines\" start=\"1\" style=\"counter-reset: li-counter 0 ;\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u0026lt;technique vs=\"LitSolid\" ps=\"LitSolid\" psdefines=\"DIFFMAP\"\u0026gt;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli class=\"selected\"\u003e    \u0026lt;pass name=\"alpha\" psdefines=\"EMISSIVEMAP\" depthwrite=\"false\" blend=\"alpha\" /\u0026gt;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e    \u0026lt;pass name=\"litalpha\" depthwrite=\"false\" blend=\"addalpha\" /\u0026gt;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e    \u0026lt;pass name=\"shadow\" vs=\"Shadow\" ps=\"Shadow\" /\u0026gt;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u0026lt;/technique\u0026gt;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\n\n  \u003c/article\u003e\n  \u003cdiv class=\"onebox-metadata\"\u003e\n    \n    \n  \u003c/div\u003e\n  \u003cdiv style=\"clear: both\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAnd it looks like emission is just additive render on top of the diffuse map? As a workaround, I made the parts that are fully lit in the emission map completely black in the diffuse map, and now it looks great in any light. But this doesn’t sound right.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAm I misusing the emission map, or is it really expected to have lit areas darken in diffuse map in order to work in all lights?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThanks,\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-01T19:48:11.237Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":76,"reads":40,"readers_count":39,"score":393.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/xamarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Shaders/HLSL/LitSolid.hlsl#L312","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"urho/LitSolid.hlsl at master · xamarin/urho · GitHub","clicks":3},{"url":"https://github.com/xamarin/urho/blob/master/Urho3D/CoreData/Techniques/DiffEmissiveAlpha.xml#L2","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"urho/DiffEmissiveAlpha.xml at master · xamarin/urho · GitHub","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37555,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-01T20:53:54.526Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"NessEngine\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/40/2060_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e NessEngine:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnd it looks like emission is just additive render on top of the diffuse map?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYes, this is correct.\u003cbr\u003e\nWhat kind of behavior you expected/wanted/find appropriate?\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-01T20:54:03.347Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":37,"readers_count":36,"score":22.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37556,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-01T20:59:39.466Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eDidn’t mean to sound like criticism \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=9\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\nBut what I expected is that emission would go into lighting calculation, meaning that emission of 1,1,1 will just be the color in the diffuse map, and not actually white.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSo if its additive, that means that if I create emission map with fully lit parts I’m expected to black them out in the diffuse texture?\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-01T20:59:39.466Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":37,"readers_count":36,"score":12.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"username":"Eugene","name":"Eugene Kozlov","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37557,"name":"SirNate0","username":"SirNate0","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/9f8e36/{size}.png","created_at":"2020-05-01T21:02:54.317Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eYou could try multiplying by it or adding it to the lighting or something, or you could try replacing the \u003ccode\u003e+=\u003c/code\u003e with an \u003ccode\u003e= Max(finalColor, cMatEmissiveColor * Sample2D(EmissiveMap, iTexCoord.xy).rgb);\u003c/code\u003e and see if one of those gets you more desirable results. (I may have the function name for Max wrong)\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-01T21:02:54.317Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":37,"readers_count":36,"score":22.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"SirNate0","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":628,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37558,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-01T21:08:17.140Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eAs you can see, light maps multiply emission with diffuse (they have to).\u003cbr\u003e\nIt cannot be default behavior because it will limit use cases of emission maps.\u003cbr\u003e\nE.g. one will be unable to create emissive black (i.e. not reflecting light) object.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-01T21:08:49.810Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":36,"readers_count":35,"score":27.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"reply_to_user":{"username":"NessEngine","name":"Ronen","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37561,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-02T07:42:17.103Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eThanks \u003ca class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/sirnate0\"\u003e@SirNate0\u003c/a\u003e, if I’d be too bothered by it ill change the shader, right now I’m ok with darkening diffuse I just wanted to make sure I’m not misusing it.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/eugene\"\u003e@Eugene\u003c/a\u003e  yeah I understand the extra use case additive gives (making areas brighter due to environmental lights + emission),  but imo its not very usable for natural surfaces and specular is more suitable for this purpose anyway. And I don’t think it worth the price of having counter intuitive textures (now instead of normal diffuse texture I need to darken areas which are lit to avoid over brightness). Also I may be wrong here because its been long since I used one of the big commercial engines, but if I recall at least in unity emission would go 0 to diffuse, not above that.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBut as I said I’m not really bothered by it, just my two cents on this matter \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=9\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-02T07:42:17.103Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":29,"readers_count":28,"score":15.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"username":"SirNate0","name":"SirNate0","avatar_template":"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/s/9f8e36/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37569,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-02T16:36:42.573Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"NessEngine\" data-post=\"6\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/40/2060_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e NessEngine:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnd I don’t think it worth the price of having counter intuitive textures\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDiffuse light is the light reflected by the object.\u003cbr\u003e\nEmission light is the light emitted by the object itself.\u003cbr\u003e\nThese types of light are completely unrelated to each other (by definition), therefore there’s no reason to have them entangled.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAlthough I admit I have made the same mistake as you, a while ago.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"NessEngine\" data-post=\"6\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/40/2060_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e NessEngine:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ebut imo its not very usable for natural surfaces and specular is more suitable for this purpose anyway\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHeated metal or lava is quite natural phenomena and I can imagine games wanting to render it.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-02T16:38:34.338Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":28,"readers_count":27,"score":10.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37570,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-02T17:24:43.248Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eEdit: never-mind I checked with other engines and it seems to be the standard so no reason for Urho to do differently. I still think emission tied with diffuse makes more sense (and doesn’t prevent heated metal or lava in any way),  but that’s just me I guess.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-02T17:36:46.807Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":7,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":25,"readers_count":24,"score":10.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":4,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"username":"Eugene","name":"Eugene Kozlov","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37571,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-02T18:04:36.538Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"NessEngine\" data-post=\"8\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/40/2060_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e NessEngine:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eand doesn’t prevent heated metal or lava in any way\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI’m now curious. How would it work?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAssume user wants animated heated metal (from almost black when cold to glowing red when heated).\u003cbr\u003e\nUser sets diffuse (which is black), emissive (grayscale mask), and emissive color multiplier.\u003cbr\u003e\nSo the metal goes from dark gray to red/orange/white when user tweaks color multiplier.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOn the other hand, if you have emissive multiplied with diffuse, you won’t get anything because black stays black no matter what you multiply it with.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-02T18:04:36.538Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":24,"readers_count":23,"score":4.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37572,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-02T18:18:34.995Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eSomething like this:\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"lightbox-wrapper\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"lightbox\" href=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/1/1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3.jpeg\" data-download-href=\"/uploads/short-url/44TDETIQpUuxegDHQLkNb8uSBQD.jpeg?dl=1\" title=\"Untitled-1\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/1/1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3_2_690x243.jpeg\" alt=\"Untitled-1\" data-base62-sha1=\"44TDETIQpUuxegDHQLkNb8uSBQD\" width=\"690\" height=\"243\" srcset=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/1/1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3_2_690x243.jpeg, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/1/1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3_2_1035x364.jpeg 1.5x, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/1/1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3_2_1380x486.jpeg 2x\" data-small-upload=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/1/1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3_2_10x10.png\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"meta\"\u003e\n\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#far-image\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003cspan class=\"filename\"\u003eUntitled-1\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"informations\"\u003e1400×494 735 KB\u003c/span\u003e\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#discourse-expand\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOr maybe I didn’t understand what you mean exactly?\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-02T18:18:34.995Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":24,"readers_count":23,"score":9.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/1/1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3.jpeg","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"1c966b2d80ac43adb4d07149d5bc6d794a50f1c3.jpeg","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37573,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-02T18:57:04.496Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eI mean that diffuse texture (without any emission applied) should correspond to cold dark metal.\u003cbr\u003e\nIt’s not the case in your example. I cannot render cold metal with such texture. Moreover, such diffuse texture will result in incorrect lighting: if I change the intensity of the incoming light, the brightness of the object will change too, which is physically incorrect for black body.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":11,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-02T18:57:39.873Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":10,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":24,"readers_count":23,"score":24.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"reply_to_user":{"username":"NessEngine","name":"Ronen","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37614,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-06T17:55:02.795Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eSorry forgot to reply.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Eugene\" data-post=\"11\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/40/902_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e Eugene:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI cannot render cold metal with such texture.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYeah I agree with this point, it is a limitation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Eugene\" data-post=\"11\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/40/902_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e Eugene:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMoreover, such diffuse texture will result in incorrect lighting: if I change the intensity of the incoming light, the brightness of the object will change too, which is physically incorrect for black body.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNot sure I understand this point, I meant in my example that black bodies will also have black emission, so lighting won’t make them brighter?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnyway I’m convinced, you were right (+ checking other engines and seeing this is the standard behavior had its impact), so feel free to explain further if you want, or not \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=9\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"\u003e Anyway it was interesting and eye opening.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":12,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-06T17:55:02.795Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":11,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":16,"readers_count":15,"score":8.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37615,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-06T18:08:48.913Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"NessEngine\" data-post=\"12\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/40/2060_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e NessEngine:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNot sure I understand this point, I meant in my example that black bodies will also have black emission, so lighting won’t make them brighter?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e“Black body” is physical term for the body that doesn’t reflect incoming light and is illuminated only by internal heat radiation.\u003cbr\u003e\nThings like lava and heated metal are quite close to theoretical black bodies.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTo render them properly you should use black (or nearly black) diffuse texture so the lighting of the object is not affected by the incoming light.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":13,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-06T18:08:48.913Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":12,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":16,"readers_count":15,"score":8.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37617,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-06T18:17:27.351Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eThanks for the clarification, but that’s not the part I didn’t understand. If the black parts of my bodies are black in both diffuse and emission, that would not be a problem (which is what I tried to show with the screenshots earlier - the darker parts which are not glowing have darker / black emission) .\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSo in this case I don’t see how multiplying the emission with diffuse, which would only reduce it, would make black bodies less black? Edit: plus in the end it all multiplied by diffuse.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThanks!\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":14,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-06T18:18:53.627Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":13,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":16,"readers_count":15,"score":8.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"username":"Eugene","name":"Eugene Kozlov","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37618,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-06T18:24:14.192Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eIf you have both black diffuse and black emission, then the object will stay black, sure.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBut if you want to have non-zero emission somewhere and you multiply emission with diffuse, you must have non-zero diffuse in the same place of the texture.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnd as soon as you have non-zero diffuse, the body is no longer black body. Therefore, you cannot render black body with non-zero emission, if you multiply diffuse and emission during rendering. Meaning that you cannot render physically realistic lava/metal/whatever.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":15,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-06T18:24:14.192Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":14,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":16,"readers_count":15,"score":8.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"reply_to_user":{"username":"NessEngine","name":"Ronen","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37619,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-06T18:32:38.807Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Eugene\" data-post=\"15\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/40/902_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e Eugene:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnd as soon as you have non-zero diffuse, the body is no longer black body. Therefore, you cannot render black body with non-zero emission, if you multiply diffuse and emission during rendering. Meaning that you cannot render physically realistic lava/metal/whatever.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAh yes, I understand what you mean now, but that’s a problem we face anyway when emission is additive like in Urho. As soon as emission is \u0026gt; 0, result pixel will never be black. That’s sort of the problem that made me investigate in the first place (not exactly black body, but something that went brighter than it should).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThanks for the info\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":16,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-06T18:32:58.447Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":15,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":16,"readers_count":15,"score":8.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37621,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-06T18:50:11.034Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"NessEngine\" data-post=\"16\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/40/2060_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e NessEngine:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ebut that’s a problem we face anyway when emission is additive like in Urho. As soon as emission is \u0026gt; 0, result pixel will never be black\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI’m talking about how the pixel reacts to the change of lighting, not the exact color itself.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAdditive emission let you make glowing material that has the same appearance regardless of the incoming light (black body).\u003cbr\u003e\nMultiplicative emission forbids it.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRegarding your initial problem—I think it stems from the fact that the textures you use were made without considering physical meaning of the diffuse/emission. Light emitted by the heated body is by definition emission, so the physically sane diffuse texture must never have any red/yellow “glowing” parts.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":17,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-06T18:50:11.034Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":16,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":15,"readers_count":14,"score":23.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":37623,"name":"Ronen","username":"NessEngine","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/nessengine/{size}/2060_2.png","created_at":"2020-05-06T18:57:36.259Z","cooked":"\u003caside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Eugene\" data-post=\"17\" data-topic=\"6133\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"title\"\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"quote-controls\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cimg alt width=\"20\" height=\"20\" src=\"https://sjc6.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/40/902_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"\u003e Eugene:\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRegarding your initial problem—I think it stems from the fact that the textures you use were made without considering physical meaning of the diffuse/emission.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\u003c/aside\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThat is a very true conclusions, the textures in questions are actually more of a cartoonish sprites than realistic materials. The discussion was hypothetical, but my use case is far from being realistic.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":18,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-05-06T18:57:36.259Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":17,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":16,"readers_count":15,"score":3.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6133,"topic_slug":"using-emission-texture-have-i-misunderstood-it","display_username":"Ronen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1136,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false}],"stream":[37554,37555,37556,37557,37558,37561,37569,37570,37571,37572,37573,37614,37615,37617,37618,37619,37621,37623]},"timeline_lookup":[[1,935],[8,934],[12,930]],"suggested_topics":[{"id":7083,"title":"Using custom models in Xamarin.Forms shared project","fancy_title":"Using custom models in Xamarin.Forms shared project","slug":"using-custom-models-in-xamarin-forms-shared-project","posts_count":3,"reply_count":1,"highest_post_number":3,"image_url":null,"created_at":"2021-12-03T08:34:21.895Z","last_posted_at":"2021-12-03T11:40:30.983Z","bumped":true,"bumped_at":"2021-12-03T11:40:30.983Z","archetype":"regular","unseen":false,"pinned":false,"unpinned":null,"visible":true,"closed":false,"archived":false,"bookmarked":null,"liked":null,"tags_d